'''James Boyle''' (born 17 May 1944) is a Scottish gangster and convicted murderer who became a sculptor and novelist after his release from prison.

==Biography==
In 1967, he was sentenced to life imprisonment for the murder of another gangland figure, William "Babs" Rooney, but released after 14 years. He has always denied killing Rooney but has acknowledged having been a violent and sometimes ruthless moneylender from the [[Gorbals]], one of the roughest areas of Glasgow. During his incarceration in the special unit of [[Barlinnie Prison]], he turned to art and wrote an autobiography, ''[[A Sense of Freedom]]'' (1977), which has since been filmed and starred [[David Hayman]] as Jimmy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/stop-the-world-i-want-to-change-it-1.792018|title=Stop the world, I want to change it|last=McGlone|first=Jackie|work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|location=Glasgow|date=26 September 1992|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref> Boyle always maintained his innocence.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/special_report/1999/08/99/edinburgh_festival_99/431661.stm|title=Jimmy Boyle's life less ordinary|work=[[BBC News]]|date=27 August 1999|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref>

Upon his release from prison on 26 October 1981 he moved to [[Edinburgh]] to continue his artistic career. He designed the largest concrete sculpture in Europe called "Gulliver" for the [[Craigmillar Festival Society]] in 1976.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/boyle-sculpture-expected-to-fetch-20-000-at-auction-1.1040386|title=Boyle sculpture expected to fetch £20,000 at auction|last=Laughlan|first=Kim|work=The Herald|location=Glasgow|date=10 July 2010|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref>

In 1983, Boyle set up the Gateway Exchange with his wife, Sarah, and artist [[Evlynn Smith]]; a charitable organisation offering art therapy workshops to recovering drug addicts and ex-convicts. Though the project secured funding from private sources (including [[Sean Connery]], [[Billy Connolly]] and [[John Paul Getty, Jr.|John Paul Getty]]) it lasted only a few years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?view=DETAILS&grid=&targetRule=10&xml=%2Fnews%2F2003%2F04%2F30%2Fdb3002.xml|title=Obituary: Evlynn Smith|accessdate=22 April 2017|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070624021554/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?view=DETAILS&grid=&targetRule=10&xml=%2Fnews%2F2003%2F04%2F30%2Fdb3002.xml |archivedate=24 June 2007}}, ''[[Daily Telegraph]]''; accessed 19 October 2007.</ref> 

Boyle has published ''Pain of Confinement: Prison Diaries'' (1984), and a novel, ''Hero of the Underworld'' (1999). The latter was adapted for a French film, ''La Rage et le Rêve des Condamnés'' (''The Anger and Dreams of the Condemned''), and won the best [[Documentary film|documentary]] prize at the Fifa [[Montreal]] awards in 2002. He also wrote a novel, ''A Stolen Smile'', which is about the theft of the ''[[Mona Lisa]]'' and how it ends up hidden on a Scottish housing estate. It was rumoured that [[Disney]] bought the film rights but Boyle has denied that.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/index.cfm?id=1236102003|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050506174657/http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/index.cfm?id=1236102003|dead-url=yes|archive-date=6 May 2005|title=Scotland on Sunday|publisher=Scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com|accessdate=31 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446321/Disney-in-2m-deal-for-novel-by-Jimmy-Boyle.html|title=Disney in £2m deal for novel by Jimmy Boyle|last=Cramb|first=Auslan|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=10 November 2003|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/2485529.stm|title=French fall for Glasgow hardman|work=[[BBC News]]|date=17 November 2002|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref>

In 1998, he was named as a financial donor of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/161057.stm|title='Luvvies' for Labour|work=BBC News|date=30 August 1998|accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref>

The character Nicky Dryden in the 1999 film ''[[The Debt Collector]]'' is reportedly loosely based on Boyle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://old.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/review/124|title=The Debt Collector|last=Kelly|first=Richard|work=[[Sight & Sound]]|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref>

He lives between France and Morocco with his second wife, Kate Fenwick, a British actress.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/21/greathomesanddestinations/17gh-morocco.html?_r=1&oref=slogin|work=The New York Times|title=In Marrakesh, Homes Among the Palm Groves|first=Seth|last=Sherwood|date=21 October 2007|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2007/feb/17/shopping.homes2|title=Je ne regrette riad|last=Harrison|first=Anthony|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=16 February 2007|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref> They married in [[Marrakech|Marrakech, Morocco]] on 27 October 2007.

