{{Infobox Politician | image = <!-- only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people - see [[WP:NONFREE]] --> | | honorific-prefix= [[The Honourable]] | name = Marie-Claude Blais | party = [[Progressive Conservative Party of New Brunswick|Progressive Conservative]] | office= Justice of the [[Court of Queen's Bench of New Brunswick]] | premier = [[Brian Gallant]] | nominator = [[Peter MacKay]] | term_start = May 5, 2015 | term_end = | predecessor = Peter S. Glennie | successor = | assembly1 = New Brunswick Legislative | constituency_AM1 = [[Moncton North]] | term_start1 = October 12, 2010 | term_end1 = September 22, 2014 | predecessor1 = [[Mike Murphy (New Brunswick politician)|Mike Murphy]] | successor1 = [[Chris Collins (Canadian politician)|Chris Collins]] | office2 = [[Office of the Attorney General (New Brunswick)|New Brunswick Attorney General]] | term_start2 = October 12, 2010 | term_end2 = September 19, 2013 | predecessor2 = [[Kelly Lamrock]] | successor2 = [[Ted Flemming (politician)|Ted Flemming]] | office3 = [[Department of Justice and Consumer Affairs|New Brunswick Minister of Justice]] | term_start3 = October 12, 2010 | term_end3 = September 19, 2013 | predecessor3 = [[Bernard LeBlanc]] | successor3 = [[Troy Lifford]] | office4 = [[Department of Education and Early Childhood Development (New Brunswick)|Minister of Education and Early Childhood Development]] | term_start4 = September 19, 2013 | term_end4 = October 7, 2014 | predecessor4 = [[Jody Carr]] | successor4 = [[Serge Rousselle]] | profession = Lawyer/Judge | signature = }}
'''Marie-Claude Blais''' is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician, who was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]] in the [[New Brunswick general election, 2010|2010 provincial election]]. She represented the electoral district of [[Moncton North]] as a member of the [[Progressive Conservative Party of New Brunswick|Progressive Conservatives]] from 2010<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/canada/nbvotes2010/ridings/023/ New Brunswick Votes 2010: Moncton North]. [[cbc.ca]], September 27, 2010.</ref> to 2014.<ref name=wave>[http://thewave.ca/news/812820486/chris-collins-victorious-moncton-centre Chris Collins Victorious in Moncton Centre] The wave, 23 September 2014</ref>
Blais is a graduate in [[law]] from the [[Université de Moncton]] and the [[Université de Sherbrooke]], and has practised law for 12 years. She has been a member of the Progressive Conservative Party of New Brunswick since 1997, and served as party executive director and legal counsel for several years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pcnb.ca/en/team/candidate_marie-claude_blais/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101209073011/http://www.pcnb.ca/en/team/candidate_marie-claude_blais/ |archivedate=2010-12-09 |df= }}</ref>
In addition to her professional activities, Blais is active in the Moncton community, and involved in parish and local community organizations. She has also participated in the organization of the campaign to finance the renovation of Aberdeen Cultural Centre, an important site of [[Acadian]] cultural life in the region.
She was sworn in on October 12, 2010 to the positions of [[Attorney-General]] and [[Department of Justice and Consumer Affairs|Minister of Justice and Consumer Affairs]] of New Brunswick in the government of [[David Alward]]. She was defeated in the 2014 general election by Liberal Chris Collins.<ref name=wave/>
In May 2015 she was appointed Justice of the Court of the Queens Bench of New Brunswick.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/marie-claude-blais-ex-pc-justice-minister-appointed-judge-1.3062938|title=Marie-Claude Blais, ex-PC justice minister, appointed judge|publisher=CBC News|date=May 6, 2015|accessdate=2018-05-05}}</ref>
