:''This individual is sometimes confused with '''[[Irene (empress)|Byzantine Empress Irene]],''' who was her daughter-in-law.'' {{Infobox monarch | name =Tzitzak | title =Empress of the Romans | image = | caption = | full name =Tzitzak (baptismal name Irene) | spouse =[[Constantine V]] | issue =[[Leo IV the Khazar]] | dynasty =[[Isaurian Dynasty]] | father =[[Bihar (Khazar)|Bihar]] | mother = | birth_date =8th century | birth_place = | death_date ={{circa}} 750 | death_place = | place of burial = }} '''Tzitzak''' ({{lang-tr|Çiçek}}; died {{circa}} 750), baptised '''Irene''' ({{lang-el|Ειρήνη}}), was a [[Khazar]] [[princess]], the daughter of ''[[khagan]]'' [[Bihar (Khazar)|Bihar]], who became empress by marriage to [[Byzantine Empire|Eastern Roman]] Emperor [[Constantine V]] (r. 741-775).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5vnQAAAAMAAJ|title=The Student's Gibbon: The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire|date=1894-01-01|page=407|publisher=Harper|language=en}}</ref>
==Empress== In 732, the [[Eastern Roman Empire]] was under threat of invasion from the [[Umayyad Caliphate]]. Seeking allies, [[Leo III the Isaurian]] sent an embassy to [[Bihar (Khazar)|Bihar]], ''[[Khagan]]'' of the [[Khazars]]. The alliance was sealed with the marriage of Tzitzak to [[Constantine V]], son and junior co-ruler of Leo.
Tzitzak was escorted to [[Constantinople]] for her marriage. Constantine was about fourteen years old, while Tzitzak may have been even younger as she would not give birth for eighteen years.{{fact|date=October 2018}} Tzitzak became a [[Christian]] under the [[baptism]]al name [[Irene (given name)|Irene]]. Tzitzak's wedding gown became famous, starting a new fashion craze in [[Constantinople]] for male robes called ''[[tzitzakion|tzitzakia]]''.
The chronicle of [[Theophanes the Confessor]] records that Tzitzak learned to read [[religious text]]s. He describes her as pious and contrasts her with the "impiety" of her father-in-law and husband. The emperors Leo III and Constantine V were [[Iconoclasm (Byzantine)|iconoclasts]] while Theophanes was an [[iconodule]] monk. His praise probably reflected the fact that Irene herself shared his views.<ref name="roman-emperors2000">[http://www.roman-emperors.org/irenev.htm "Irene, wife of Constantine V" (2000)]</ref>
It is uncertain whether her mother-in-law [[Maria, wife of Leo III|Maria]] was still the senior empress at the time of Tzitzak's marriage. Leo III died on 18 June 741. Constantine V succeeded him with Irene as his empress consort. However, civil war broke out almost immediately as [[Artabasdos]], brother-in-law of Constantine, claimed the throne for himself. The civil war lasted until 2 November 743. The role of Irene in the war is not described by Theophanes.
On 25 January 750, Constantine and Tzitzak had a son, Leo, who would succeed his father as [[Leo IV the Khazar|Emperor Leo IV]]—better known as "Leo the Khazar". Leo's birth is the last mention of Irene in the historical record. By the following year, Constantine was already married to his second wife [[Maria, wife of Constantine V|Maria]]. Lynda Garland has suggested Tzitzak died in childbirth.<ref name="roman-emperors2000"/>
The word ''tzitzak'' is most likely a [[Greek language|Hellenized]] version of the [[Turkic languages|Turkic]] word ''[[:wiktionary:çiçek|çiçek]]'', meaning "flower."
